column3:
Many of today's conversations include the words COVID-19 and Health Disparity.  Be informed so that you can be part of the discussion without bias and reduce disparities within your social reach.  NIH and @NIHNINDS is working to address health care disparities across the country in this conversation with American Academy of Neurology.  
This content is made available for voluntary, informational purposes and does not constitute medical or legal advice.

The Mediterranean diet, which emphasizes fruits, vegetables, whole grains, legumes, fish, and other seafood; unsaturated fats such as olive oils; and low amounts of red meat, eggs, and sweets is promising evidence that lifestyle changes can benefit brain health. 

A variation of this, called MIND (Mediterranean–DASH Intervention for Neurodegenerative Delay) incorporates the DASH (Dietary Approaches to Stop Hypertension) diet, which has been shown to lower high blood pressure, a risk factor for Alzheimer’s disease.  
More information about benefits of change in our diet can be found at: https://www.nia.nih.gov/health/what-do-we-know-about-diet-and-prevention-alzheimers-disease

Crystal M. Glover, PhD will be one of our Keynote Speakers at the IADRC's 14th Annual Martin Family Alzheimer's Disease Caregiver Symposium: Diversity and Disparity in Alzheimer’s Disease.  Symposium will be held virtually on Friday, September 25.

IADRC presented it's annual Memory University 2020 in virtual format.  

The theme was Brainpower: Staying Sharp at All Ages.  Dr. Sophia Wang, MD presented the 4th week's session titled "Genes and Brain Scans: What’s My Risk of Getting Alzheimer’s Disease?" 

Dr. Wang is an Assistant professor of Clinical Psychiatry and Outreach and Recruitment Core Leader of the Indiana Alzheimer’s Disease Research Center at Indiana University School of Medicine. 

You are invited to watch the FULL presentation here:  https://iu.mediaspace.kaltura.com/media/Mem-U_June_26_2020-Wang-edited/1_p5blskh0

One of our exceptional IADRC Community Advisory members, Mollie Richards, has been staying busy and continuing to support the community throughout the COVID-19 pandemic.  Mollie recently shared:

 “Covid-19 requires multiple changes to daily life.  One of the primary changes for me was staying busy.  My volunteer, opportunities for Community Hospital, the Alzheimer’s Association Greater Indiana Chapter and Indiana Alzheimer’s Disease Research Center closed or transitioned.  How was I going to keep occupied? I was a part of a group email asking for volunteers to sew DYI facemasks for one of the hospitals.  My sewing machine had been “in mothballs” for about 10 years.  I was able to get it working with a goal of making 50 facemasks. As of today, I have produced and donated over 150 facemasks  with a goal of making 200.”   

Thank you, Mollie for your hard work and dedication to keeping our communities safe.

Introducing "Ask The Doctor," our monthly series featuring outstanding clinicians from the IADRC answering your questions!

September's focus will be Frontotemporal Dementia (FTD). FTD is an umbrella term used to describe a group of uncommon brain disorders characterized by atrophy, or shrinking, of the frontal and temporal lobes of the brain. 

FTD is often misdiagnosed as psychiatric problems due to the way it can impact behavior and personality. It is also often misdiagnosed as Alzheimer's Disease due to the language and memory changes it may cause.

Message us via Facebook Messenger or send your questions to iadcevt@iu.edu for an opportunity to have Dr. Clark answer here!

This weekend, the IADRC's Outreach, Recruitment, and Engagement Core Leader, Dr. Sophia Wang appeared alongside Community Advisory Board Co-Chair, Ralph Richards, and member Mollie Richards for an incredible conversation with Radio Next's Harold HB Bell. 

Listen along to hear some beautiful and powerful words from Mollie, sharing her experiences fighting for civil rights and marching alongside Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. 

In addition, Mollie and Dr. Wang explain the role of stress and trauma, including generational-trauma caused by slavery and racism influences health equity and outcomes today. 

Learn more about the research being conducted at the IADRC and the upcoming Martin Caregiver Symposium by following along and please be sure to share with your friends and family.

The Alzheimer's Association Greater Indiana Chapter will be hosting their 2020 Day of Learning on August 21, 2020. Learn about the incredible work your Indiana chapter is doing to move the mission forward in our journey to end Alzheimer's Disease. 

This even will be virtual and includes a full day of informational seminars that you can join. 

Register here: https://www.communityresourcefinder.org/ResourceView/Index?id=1945510&profileDefinitionId=93&fbclid=IwAR1bfudG5QiVaxS7TLp3ijL-4k4oGf17qJdY3Noluihp1JW-ZWp2Z_7tz4Y

The IADRC's Dr. Sophia Wang discusses the impact of COVID-19 on those experiencing dementia as well as their caregivers in this episode of  AARP Indiana's "Ask The Doc" series. She also shares some tips & tricks for navigating these challenging times. 

Watch & share with your friends and family for information & to raise awareness of the unique difficulties caregivers may be experiencing during the pandemic.

Dr. Carl Hill explains the development of the Health Disparities Research Framework to explore the environmental, sociocultural, behavioral, and biological determinants of health disparities related to aging.

Dr. Carl Hill will be one of our Keynote Speakers at this year's 14th Annual Martin Family Alzheimer's Disease Caregiver Symposium: Diversity and Disparity in Alzheimer’s Disease

The IADRC & CICOA Aging & In-Home Solutions is proud to present the 14th Annual Martin Family Alzheimer's Disease Symposium: "Diversity and Disparity in Alzheimer’s Disease:
Understanding the Past, Seeking Hope for the Future"

We are excited to announce Dr. Crystal Glover, PhD and Dr. Carl Hill, PhD, MPH as this year's keynote speakers. 

The event will also commemorate the incredible life and work for Dr.  Mary Guerriero Austrom, PhD. 

This year's event will be 100% virtual & registration is NOW open (https://redcap.uits.iu.edu/surveys/index.php?s=LXHP3YLPWX). Follow the link on the event page to register and be sure to click "attending"  or "interested" for updates on the event. 

Please feel free to reach out to us via messenger if you have any questions or concerns. We are excited to (virtually) see many new and returning faces at the symposium in September!
